                  "code": "67781-5",
                  "display": "Summarization of encounter note"
                }
              ]
            },
            "title": "Synthesis"
          },
          {
            "text": {
              "status": "generated",
              "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">Dear colleague, I am writing to inform you about the hospital course of your 90-year-old male patient, admitted on 29/08/2009 with acute chest pain and electrocardiographic changes consistent with Non-ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction (NSTEMI). On admission, troponin levels were significantly elevated, confirming myocardial injury. Echocardiography revealed regional wall motion abnormalities. The patient underwent urgent coronary angiography, demonstrating significant coronary artery disease, followed by successful Percutaneous Coronary Intervention (PCI) with stent implantation to the culprit lesion. Post-procedurally, the patient remained hemodynamically stable. Dual antiplatelet therapy was initiated alongside optimised medical management including anticoagulation, beta-blocker, statin, and ACE inhibitor. The patient was discharged home on 30/08/2009 in a stable condition. Please ensure close follow-up, medication compliance, and cardiac rehabilitation referral. Do not hesitate to contact me for further information.</div>"
            },
            "code": {
              "coding": [
                {
